            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Getting an option value will now incur the cost of a dictionary and a table allocation, along with fetching all the option info which is seldom used compared to the value.\r\n\r\nI will provide benchmarks to see if this matters. I suspect resolving an option value is the main cost, not the option properties. Table allocation is likely negligible compared to resolving the value of a Vim option.\r\n\r\n> I'm not really a fan of APIs with polymorphic return types as it makes it difficult/impossible to add accurate type annotations.\r\n\r\n `nvim_get_option_value`  returns `Object`, how does this PR regress anything?\r\n\r\nThe main problem being solved here is that we have 2 separate awkwardly-named APIs for vague \"performance\" reasons, but options are slow for other reasons, not because of the RPC payload. I raised this question during development of `nvim_get_option_info2` and I don't think it was answered.",
