            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Getting an option value will now incur the cost of a dictionary and a table allocation, along with fetching all the option info which is seldom used compared to the value.\r\n\r\nJust to note, one way to avoid the dictionary allocation is to add a `lstate` argument to the function, and if present, build the table directly onto the Lua stack and avoid the arena middle-man.\r\n\r\nWe did this for `nvim_buf_get_lines` and it resulted in a 30% gain in performance. Not magnitudes, but still worth doing.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n> nvim_get_option_value returns Object, how does this PR regress anything?\r\n\r\nSorry, I wasn't sure on the exact direction of this, but can see the value is a `value` field in a returned object.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nOne thing that was nice about `nvim_get_option_value` was it that it had symmetry with `nvim_set_option_value`. With this PR we will end up with: `nvim_get_option` and `nvim_set_option_value` which feels a little off. Maybe we could rename `nvim_set_option_value` to just `nvim_set_option`?\r\n\r\nWith all that said, my preference would be to just leave things as they are, but I appreciate the arguments for doing this and hopefully the perf loss is negligible.\r\n\r\nMaybe one compromise would be to return a tuple `(value, info)`, where `info` is only returned if asked for, similar to `nvim_buf_get_extmark_by_id`? We still have to allocate a table, but at least the info becomes optional.",
